{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 INFERNO CANTO 26}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Matching the ironic apostrophe of Pistoia that follows the departure of Vanni Fucci \softline
in the last canto (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXV.10-12), this one of Florence comes in the wake of the poem's \softline
departure from the five Florentine thieves.  The image of Florence as winged has caused some \softline
puzzlement.  While commentators, beginning perhaps with Scartazzini/Vandelli, point out that \softline
Dante's words most probably echo the Latin inscription, dating to 1255, on the fa{\f2\u231\'e7}ade of the \softline
Florentine Palazzo del Podest{\f3 \'42}, proclaiming that Florence is in possession of the sea, the land, \softline
indeed the entire world, we are still left to speculate on Dante's reasons for presenting her as \softline
winged.  Whatever his reason, we might want to reflect that he thought of himself as the 'wing{\f3 \'50}d \softline
one' because of the easy pun available from his surname, Alighieri, in Latin 'aliger' (winged).  See \softline
Hugh Shankland, "Dante 'Aliger,'" }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Modern Language Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  70 (1975), pp. 764-85; "Dante \softline
'Aliger' and Ulysses," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Italian Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  32 (1977), pp. 21-40.  In this canto the apostrophised city \softline
and the seafaring Ulysses are both associated with 'wings' ('in our mad flight we turned our oars to \softline
wings' [v. 125 -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.125]); at least intrinsically, the protagonist is also.  He is on a better-purposed 'flight.'  For these motifs and another related one see Maria Corti, "On the Metaphors of \softline
Sailing, Flight, and Tongues of Fire in the Episode of Ulysses (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . 26)," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Stanford Italian Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
9 (1990), pp. 33-47.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The text alludes to the classical and medieval belief that morning dreams were more \softline
truthful in their content than any others.  Guido da Pisa is the first (but hardly the last) to refer to \softline
a text in Ovid to this effect (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Heroides}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XIX.195-196).  On this subject see Charles Speroni's \softline
article, "Dante's Prophetic Morning-Dreams," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Philology}{\plain \fs24 \f1  45 (1948), pp. 50-59.  And \softline
see, for the same view of morning dreams, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX.16-18.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 8-12.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The passage about Prato has caused two interpretive problems: (1) Does it refer to \softline
the anger felt by Cardinal Niccol{\f3 \'62} da Prato when he failed to bring peace between the warring \softline
Florentine factions in 1304 or to the rebellion of the town of Prato in 1309, when Florence's small \softline
neighbor cast out its Black Guelphs?  (2) Is Dante heartened or heart-sick as he contemplates this \softline
'future' event?\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab It was only in the eighteenth century that a commentator, Pompeo Venturi, suggested a \softline
reference to the cardinal (comm. to XXVI.9).  Further, since the second event was probably \softline
roughly contemporaneous to the writing of this canto, it seems likely that Dante would have \softline
enjoyed having so recent a piece of news as confirmation of his 'prophecy.'  As to his emotions, it \softline
seems more reasonable to reflect that Dante is admitting that he will only be happy once the \softline
power of the Black Guelphs of Florence is destroyed; he is in pain as he awaits that liberation.  In \softline
other words, this is not an expression of sadness for the city's coming tribulation, but a desire to \softline
see them come to pass -- and that is the common view of the early commentators.  As Poletto was \softline
perhaps the first commentator to note (in 1894), the passage is very like one found in one of \softline
Dante's 'political epistles' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistle}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.17), when he hopes that the invading forces of Emperor \softline
Henry VII will liberate the city.  As Chiavacci Leonardi observes (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno, con il commento di A. \softline
M. C. L.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Milan: Mondadori, 1991], p. 794), according to the chronicle of Giovanni Villani, news \softline
of Henry's election in 1308 was causing excited imperialist hopes all through Italy in 1309.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 14.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   While we do not believe that Dante says here what Petrocchi says he does, we have, 
as always, followed his text, which reads }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 iborni}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (pallid, the color and coolness of ivory) and not, \softline
as the text had previously stood, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 i borni}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (the outcroppings of the rocks).  In our opinion the 'old' \softline
reading is the superior one.  Instead of 'on those stairs that turned us pale when we came down' \softline
we would say 'on the stairs the jutting rocks had made for our descent.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The steepness of the rock causes Dante to find hand-holds on the wall as he mounts.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19-24.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   According to Lino Pertile ("Dante e l'ingegno di Ulisse," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Stanford Italian Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
1 [1979], pp. 35-65), those who propose a negative view of Ulysses fail to acknowledge the \softline
importance of these verses, which reveal the poet's sympathy for the Greek hero even now as he \softline
writes of him.  He cites (p. 37) Ovid (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIII.135-139) in support of his argument.  \softline
However, that text offers Ulysses' vaunt of his own worthiness to receive the arms of Achilles \softline
(denying the claims of Ajax), and the entire passage gives us the portrait of a figure full of pride \softline
and self-love.  See Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Princeton: Princeton University \softline
Press, 1969), pp. 115-16, arguing that Dante, in this passage, is fully conscious of his previous \softline
'Ulyssean' efforts, undertaken by his venturesome and prideful intellect, and now hopes to keep \softline
them under control.  Castelvetro's reading of the passage is in this vein; according to him the poet \softline
grieves 'for having improperly put to use my genius' (comm. to vv. 19-22).  Dante hopes, in other \softline
words, to be exactly }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 unlike}{\plain \fs24 \f1  Ulysses.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab In a lecture at Dartmouth College in the early 1980s Prof. Rachel Jacoff pointed out that \softline
Dante's verb for his necessary restraint, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 affreno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ('rein in,' 'curb'), reflects precisely what Phaeton \softline
failed to do, rein in his steeds: 'Fetonte abbandon{\f3 \'62} li freni' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVII.107).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 25-30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The first of two elaborate similes in prologue to the appearance of Ulysses deals \softline
with the number of the false counsellors: they are numerous as fireflies.  Dante, as peasant (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 il \softline
villano}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) resting on his hillside (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 poggio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  -- Frankel ["The Context of Dante's Ulysses: the Similes in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  104 (1986), pp. 102-5]) contrasts his 'humble' hillock with Ulysses' \softline
'prideful' mountain [verse 133], looks out upon this valley full of fireflies.  This peaceful scene \softline
lulls many readers into a sort of moral exemption for Ulysses; if he looks so pleasant, how can he \softline
be seen as sinful?  In fact the distancing effect of the simile makes Ulysses seem small and \softline
relatively insignificant.  We can imagine how he might feel, told that he had been compared to a \softline
firefly.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Many readers are rightly reminded of the previous simile involving a rustic (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lo villanello}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) \softline
at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIV.7-15.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For the flames as reminiscent of the Epistle of James (James 3:4-6) see Richard Bates \softline
and Thomas Rendall ("Dante's Ulysses and the Epistle of James," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  107 [1989], pp. \softline
33-44) and Alison Cornish ("The Epistle of James in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  26," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Traditio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  45 [1989-90], pp. 367-79): 'Behold also the ships, which though they be so great, and are driven by fierce winds, yet are \softline
turned about with a very small helm, wherever the steersman pleases.  Even so the tongue is a \softline
little member, and boasts many things.  Behold how great a matter a little fire kindles!  And the \softline
tongue is a fire, a world of iniquity: so is the tongue among our members, that it defiles the whole \softline
body, and sets on fire the course of nature, and it is set on fire of hell.'  Pietro di Dante was the \softline
first to cite this passage in connection with Dante's description of the flames here (Pietro1, comm. \softline
to vv. 31-33), and also refers to it in both later redactions of his commentary.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The second Ulyssean simile describes the flame-wrapped appearance of Ulysses in \softline
terms of Elijah's fiery ascent to Heaven.  Perhaps the first extended discussion of the biblical text \softline
behind the passage was offered by Margherita Frankel ("The Context of Dante's Ulysses: the \softline
Similes in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  104 [1986]), pp. 110-16, who argues that, while Elijah \softline
is seen as antithetical to Ulysses (see Anthony K. Cassell, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Fearful Art of Justice}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1984], pp. 88-93), Dante is also seen as related to the \softline
negative aspect of Elisha (his pride in taking on the prophet's mantle) -- see II Kings 2:9-12.  She \softline
is answered by Luisa Ferretti Cuomo ("La polisemia delle similitudini nella }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Divina Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  \softline
Eliseo: un caso esemplare," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Strumenti critici}{\plain \fs24 \f1  10 n.s. [1995], pp. 105-42) who regards Elisha as \softline
only a positive figure of Dante, similarly accepting his role as successor prophet.  For the same \softline
view see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Princeton: Princeton University Press, \softline
1969), p. 117.  See also Kablitz ("Il canto di Ulisse [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI] agli occhi dei commentatori \softline
contemporanei e delle indagini moderne," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Letteratura italiana antica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2 [2001], pp. 74-84), who \softline
also argues against Frankel's interpretation, but seems unaware of Ferretti Cuomo's work.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Elisha was avenged by the bears in that the forty-two children who mocked his prophetic \softline
calling, addressing him as 'Baldy' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 calve}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), were attacked and lacerated by two bears (II Kings \softline
2:23-24).  For the biblical resonance of this scene see Paola Rigo, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Memoria classica e memoria \softline
biblica in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Florence: Olschki, 1994), pp. 51-54.  Dante refers to this incident in one of his \softline
'political epistles' (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.8-12): }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistle}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.16.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 43-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The protagonist's excitement at the prospect of seeing Ulysses is evident (Ulysses \softline
has not been identified yet, but the poet seems to be taking a liberty in allowing his character to \softline
fathom who is about to appear).  In his reckless abandon to gain experience of this great sinner, \softline
he resembles Ulysses himself.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 48.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's point seems to be that each of the flame-enclosed sinners is covered by the \softline
external sign of their inner ardor, their longing to captivate the minds of those upon whom they \softline
practiced their fraudulent work.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 52-54.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Almost all commentators point to the passage in Statius (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Theb}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII.429-432) that \softline
describes the immolation of the corpses of the two warring brothers, Eteocles and Polynices, \softline
whose enmity was the root of the civil war in Thebes and is manifest now even in their death, as \softline
the smoke from their burning bodies will not join.  Among the early commentators only Pietro di \softline
Dante (Pietro1, comm. to vv. 52-56) noticed that the same scene is reported in similar ways in \softline
Lucan as well (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Phars}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.551-552).  Some dozen or more modern commentators, from Venturi on, \softline
have also done so.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 55-57.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Ulysses and Diomedes are clearly indicated as suffering the punishment of God for \softline
their fraudulent acts; yet this indictment has not kept readers from admiring them -- or at least \softline
Ulysses.  Perhaps the central problem in the large debate that has surrounded Dante's version of \softline
the Greek hero in the last century and a half is how sympathetically we are meant to respond to \softline
him.  To put that another way, what is the nature of Ulysses' sin, and how urgently is it meant to \softline
govern the reader's sense of his worth?  And a further complication is of more recent vintage: \softline
what should we make of the at least apparent similarity between Ulysses and Dante himself?  \softline
Chiavacci Leonardi has made a useful distinction between the two essential attitudes that 
distinguish divergent readings of the undoubtedly heroic figure (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno, con il commento di A. \softline
M. C. L.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Milan: Mondadori, 1991], p. 762): (1) Ulysses is marked by greatness; he is unfortunate \softline
but guiltless; (2) he is characterized by the sin of pride, like Adam.  For an example of the first \softline
view see Francesco De Sanctis in 1870: Dante 'erects a statue to this precursor of Christopher \softline
Columbus, a pyramid set in the mud of hell' (Francesco De Sanctis, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Storia della letteratura \softline
italiana}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , 4th ed. [Bari: Laterza, 1949 (1870)], pp. 201-2).  For similar views see Benedetto Croce \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La poesia di Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , 2nd ed. [Bari: Laterza, 1921]), p. 98, and Mario Fubini ("Il peccato \softline
d'Ulisse" and "Il canto XXVI dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Il peccato d'Ulisse e altri scritti danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Milan: Ricciardi, 1966]), pp. 1-76.  Attilio Momigliano (comm. to  XXVI.64-69) throws all \softline
caution to the wind.  He complains that the first 63 verses of the canto are too dry and erudite.  \softline
Now that Ulysses is on the scene, we breathe the air of true and enthusiastic poetry.  \softline
'Appearances notwithstanding,' he says, 'Dante not only does not condemn the fraudulent acts of \softline
Ulysses and Diomedes, he exalts them.'  Among contemporaries, Lino Pertile is essentially in this \softline
camp ("Dante e l'ingegno di Ulisse," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Stanford Italian Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  1 [1979], pp. 35-65).  The negative \softline
view in modern discussions was enunciated clearly by Bruno Nardi ("La tragedia di Ulisse," in his \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante e la cultura medievale}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Bari: Laterza, 1942], pp. 89-99).  See also Julius Wilhelm, "Die \softline
Gestalt des Odysseus in Dantes }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 G{\f2\u246\'f6}ttlicher Kom{\f2\u246\'f6}die,}{\plain \fs24 \f1 "}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Deutsches Dante-Jahrbuch}{\plain \fs24 \f1  38 (1960), pp. \softline
75-93; Giorgio Padoan ("Ulisse 'fandi fictor' e le vie della sapienza. Momenti di una tradizione [da \softline
Virgilio a Dante]," in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Il pio Enea e l'empio Ulisse: Tradizione classica e intendimento \softline
medievale in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Ravenna: Longo, 1977 (1960)], pp. 170-99); Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's \softline
"Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1969]), pp. 114-23; Scott ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI: \softline
Dante's Ulysses," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lettere Italiane}{\plain \fs24 \f1  23 (1971), pp. 145-86; Iannucci ("Ulysses' }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 folle volo}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : the \softline
Burden of History," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Medioevo romanzo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  3 [1976]. pp. 410-45).  Recently a third 'school' has \softline
opened its doors, one that finds Ulysses less than totally admirable and yet associated with Dante, \softline
who presents himself, just beneath the lines of his text, as a trespassing voyager himself.  See \softline
Mazzotta ("Poetics of History: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Diacritics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [summer 1975], p. 41; Stierle \softline
("Odysseus und Aeneas: Eine typologische Konfiguration in Dantes }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Divina Commedia,}{\plain \fs24 \f1 " in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Das \softline
fremde Wort: Studien zur Interdependenz von Texten}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Festschrift f{\f2\u252\'fc}r Karl Maurer zum 60. \softline
Geburtstag}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Ilse Nolting-Hauff & Joachim Schulze [Amsterdam: B. R. Gr{\f2\u252\'fc}ner, 1988], pp. \softline
111-54); Barolini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Undivine "Comedy": Detheologizing Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton \softline
University Press, 1992], }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 passim}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ); Bloom ("The Strangeness of Dante: Ulysses and Beatrice," in \softline
his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Western Canon: The Books and the School of the Ages}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [New York: Harcourt Brace, \softline
1994], pp. 85-89).  For a rejoinder to the position of these critics see Stull and Hollander ("The \softline
Lucanian Source of Dante's Ulysses," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  63 (1991 [1997]), pp. 43-52.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 58-63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil lists the sins of the two heroes: the stratagem of the troop-hiding Trojan \softline
horse (with which Ulysses, if not Diomedes, is associated in Virgil, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II); Ulysses' trickery in \softline
getting Achilles to join the war against Troy, thus abandoning, on the isle of Scyros, his beloved \softline
Deidamia (as recounted in Statius's unfinished }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Achilleid}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), who subsequently died of grief at the \softline
news of his death in Troy; the joint adventure in which they stole the Palladium, image of Athena, \softline
a large wooden statue, in return for which the horse served as a fraudulent peace-offering (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
II.163-169).  Those who, like Momigliano, believe that the fraudulent acts of Ulysses and \softline
Diomedes are exalted by Dante, should be reminded that Virgil, in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , is pretty hard on \softline
them.  Diomedes, for his part in the theft of the Palladium, is impious (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 impius}{\plain \fs24 \f1  -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.163), \softline
while Ulysses is called an 'inventor of crimes' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scelerum... inventor}{\plain \fs24 \f1  -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.164).  It seems more 
than likely that Dante would have shared Virgil's views of these matters.  For the recovery of the \softline
notion, widespread in the ancient commentators, that Ulysses is best described as 'astutus' (in the \softline
sense of possessing low cunning) see Richard Kay, "Two Pairs of Tricks: Ulysses and Guido in \softline
Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI-XXVII," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Quaderni d'italianistica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  1 (1980), pp. 107-24; John Ahern, \softline
"Dante's Slyness: The Unnamed Sin of the Eighth Bolgia," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Romanic Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  73 (1982), pp. 275-91.  For further discussion of the importance of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 astutia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to Dante's conception of Ulysses see Stull \softline
and Hollander, "The Lucanian Source of Dante's Ulysses," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  63 (1991 [1997]), pp. \softline
49-50.\par
