XXVI.91-93).  Thus does Ulysses put himself forward as a rivalrous competitor of Virgil's hero.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-99.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Ulysses' aim, to discover the truth about the world and about mankind, sounds \softline
acceptable or even heroic to many contemporary readers.  When we examine the prologue to this \softline
thought, in which he denies his family feeling for Telemachus, Laertes, and Penelope in order to \softline
make his voyage, we may begin to see the inverted parallelism to the hero whom he would 
emulate and best, Aeneas, loyal to Ascanius, Anchises, and Creusa.  If Ulysses is venturesome, \softline
Aeneas is, as Virgil hardly tires of calling him, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 pius}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , a 'family man' if ever there was one.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 100-111.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   He and his crew of aging, tired sailors head out across the Mediterranean from \softline
Italy and reach the gates of Hercules, the very sign, even as Ulysses reports it, of the end of the \softline
known world.  While Dante does not refer to it (nor to the previous voyages of Marco Polo), a \softline
number of recent commentators speculate that he was aware of the voyage of the Vivaldi brothers \softline
in 1291.  They, in search of India, sailed out through the Strait of Gibraltar, having passed Spain \softline
and Africa, and were never heard from again.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112-113.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   It is a commonplace in the commentaries to believe that the opening words of \softline
Ulysses' speech to his men reflect the first words of Aeneas to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 his}{\plain \fs24 \f1  men (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.198).  Several, \softline
